sdp/verification/t-005@20260530t002730z-verify.md:61:{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":"2026-05-30T01:04:22.194Z","tool_name":"write_file","tool_id":"write_file_1780103062194_1","parameters":{"file_path":"sdp/verification/t-005 @20260530t002730z-verify.md","content":"# Verification Report — T-005 @sdp/logs/Verify_T-005_20260530T002730Z_1780102989.log\n\n**Verify Agent:** Gemini CLI\n**Date:** Friday, May 29, 2026\n**Artifacts Reviewed:**\n- `promptclaw/asset_bus/atomic.py`\n- `promptclaw/asset_bus/__init__.py`\n- `tests/test_asset_bus_atomic.py`\n\n## Correctness\nThe implementation correctly ensures atomic writes for manifest and produced files.\n- `atomic_write_bytes` writes to a `<path>.tmp` file, calls `flush()` and `os.fsync()` on the file handle to ensure durability, and then uses `os.replace()` to move it to the final destination.\n- `os.replace` is atomic on POSIX and Windows (overwriting existing files), satisfying the core requirement.\n- The use of `BaseException` in the `try...except` block ensures that the temporary file is cleaned up even on interruptions like `KeyboardInterrupt`.\n\n## Completeness\nThe task requirements are fully met:\n- All writes go through a temp path and `os.replace`.\n- No partial file is observable (verified by `test_atomic_write_no_partial_observed_by_concurrent_reader`).\n- Parent directories are automatically created if missing.\n- Cleanup of temporary files on failure is implemented and tested.\n\n## Consistency\nThe implementation is consistent with the `promptclaw` codebase:\n- Follows the subpackage structure in `promptclaw/asset_bus/`.\n- Uses `pathlib.Path` consistently.\n- Adheres to the established error handling and testing patterns.\n\n## Security\nWhile primarily a correctness task, the implementation improves security by:\n- Preventing race conditions where a requester might read a partial or corrupted manifest.\n- Ensuring that failures during write do not leave stale temporary files that could clutter the bus.\n\n## Quality\nThe implementation is high quality:\n- `os.fsync()` provides strong durability guarantees.\n- The tests are comprehensive, especially the concurrency test which uses a separate thread to attempt to observe partial writes.\n- `ruff` and `mypy` checks pass.\n- All 11 tests in `tests/test_asset_bus_atomic.py` pass.\n\n## Issues Found\n- None.\n\n## Verdict: PASS\n\n## Notes for Lead Agent\nThe atomic write helpers are robust and ready to be used in the producer loop (DAB-040) and other components that write to the bus. The inclusion of `os.fsync()` is a commendable hardening step for durability.\n"}}
